## Setup
library(bdots)

setwd("~/tmp/noise/")
data <- fread("NS1 fh-sh local effect.txt")

## Original fit
fit <- bdotsFit(data = data,
                subject = "subjectID",
                time = "rTime",
                y = "TUR",
                group = c("Condition", "Half"),
                curveType = logistic(),
                cores = 7)

## Refit
new_param <- fread("NS1 fh-sh refit.txt")
refit <- bdotsRefit(fit, paramDT = new_param)

## Bootstrap with refit parameters
boot <- bdotsBoot(formula = diffs(TUR, Condition(Quiet, ExpectNoise)) ~ Half(FH, SH),
                    bdObj = refit,
                    Niter = 1000,
                    alpha = 0.05,
                    padj = "oleson",
                    cores = 7)

## Bootstrap with original fit
boot2 <- bdotsBoot(formula = diffs(TUR, Condition(Quiet, ExpectNoise)) ~ Half(FH, SH),
                  bdObj = fit,
                  Niter = 1000,
                  alpha = 0.05,
                  padj = "oleson",
                  cores = 7)

Ok, so this document has a view things:

  1. Manually fit bootstrapped curves and differences using the refit parameters (FH, SH, diff of diff)
  2. Manually fit bootstrapped curves and differences using the parameters originally returned by bdotsFit (FH, SH, diff of diff)
  3. Provided both side by side (FH, SH, diff of diff)

Using the original model parameters gives me results closer to what you see in excel. I’m not sure entirely why this is, but I’ll look through the refitting function to see if anything weird is happening. It may be the case in this particular situation that bdots returns better parameter estimates than matlab. Looking at the fit codes between, this seems to hold some weight

table(fit$fitCode)
## 
##   0   1   2 
## 131  12   1
table(refit$fitCode)
## 
##   0   1   3 
## 128  13   3

At any rate, feel free to compare these and see if it makes sense. There is an option at the top of the page to download the code that produced this if you want to tweak/make adjustments. There is quite a bit of copy/paste, so hopefully you don’t expect it to look too pretty

Refit Parameters

Here are results from the bootstrap using the refit parameters

First Half (refit pars)

Plots of fits for first half, expect noise and quiet, as well as difference between them.

Here, notice that EN is larger than Q until around 200 (this is the 200th time point, not time 200), they cross, with Q being larger. As the difference here is EN - Q, we see that the difference curve starts positive, ends negative.

Also worth noting here is the size of the scale – in the first plot, we see the curves are pretty similar, so the difference between the two isn’t huge. This is reflected in the second plot, where the difference values range between about -0.02 and 0.02

Second Half (refit pars)

Here is the same for the second half

EN and Q are slightly different in this case, with EN being larger than Q at both the beginning and thend, but not between around 180 and 300. Also note that the differences here are quite a bit larger. This is all reflected in the second, which begins and ends positive, with that large difference around 250 resulting in the large negative spike.

Difference of Halves (refit pars)

Here is, again, the plot of differences typically returned by bdots, but done manually. You’ll see that both of the difference curves for FH and SH look as they do above, but there is a very large magnitude of difference between the differences. FH has differences between -0.02 and 0.02, while SH has differences between -0.4 and 0.2, nearly 40 times in size. As such, subtracting the two is basically just taking the negative of SH (since FH is nearly 0), and what we end up with in the difference of difference plot is nearly just the negative of SH, which makes it look flipped
